She's my boss.
Also yours, by the way.

251
00:11:44,083 --> 00:11:45,550
You'd listen, then tell her
she's being an idiot,

252
00:11:45,634 --> 00:11:47,001
and do whatever you want.

253
00:11:47,069 --> 00:11:48,186
I find I can skip
the idiot part

254
00:11:48,270 --> 00:11:49,471
when she's not
being an idiot,

255
00:11:49,522 --> 00:11:50,755
<i>and since the scare test</i>

256
00:11:50,823 --> 00:11:52,157
<i>would have led</i>
<i>to the same dead end,</i>

257
00:11:52,224 --> 00:11:53,558
she was right to stop it.

258
00:11:53,642 --> 00:11:55,894
Which means
your problem's about you.

259
00:11:55,978 --> 00:11:57,362
This should be interesting.

260
00:11:57,446 --> 00:11:59,063
Losers love company.

261
00:11:59,148 --> 00:12:01,399
And if even
a misanthrope like me

262
00:12:01,484 --> 00:12:02,901
has a chance at happiness,

263
00:12:02,985 --> 00:12:04,486
it's gonna be pretty lonely

264
00:12:04,537 --> 00:12:06,337
on that landfill
of loserdom

265
00:12:06,405 --> 00:12:08,439
you call a mriage.

266
00:12:08,507 --> 00:12:09,941
Heart, kidneys, go.

267
00:12:10,009 --> 00:12:11,843
Could be fabry disease.

268
00:12:11,911 --> 00:12:13,545
Lipid deposition
in her tissues.

269
00:12:13,612 --> 00:12:14,829
Dad's history was clean.

270
00:12:14,897 --> 00:12:15,980
<i>What about</i>
<i>protein deposits?</i>

271
00:12:16,048 --> 00:12:18,149
They wouldn't show
in her parents' history.

272
00:12:18,217 --> 00:12:20,134
Amyloidosis.

273
00:12:20,202 --> 00:12:22,170
Explains both
the symptoms.

274
00:12:22,221 --> 00:12:23,371
Marrow transplant
to treat.

275
00:12:23,422 --> 00:12:24,872
Brother's a match.

276
00:12:24,924 --> 00:12:27,542
Confirm and do.

277
00:12:30,279 --> 00:12:31,329
I been
experiencing fatigue,

278
00:12:31,397 --> 00:12:33,932
and--and weakness.

279
00:12:34,016 --> 00:12:35,600
Wouldn't have anything
to do with the fact

280
00:12:35,684 --> 00:12:39,137
that you're...
102 years old.

281
00:12:39,205 --> 00:12:40,688
Usually
he's strong as an ox.

282
00:12:40,739 --> 00:12:42,524
102-year-old ox.

283
00:12:42,575 --> 00:12:45,026
He has tingling
in his feet and his legs.

284
00:12:45,077 --> 00:12:47,328
I want a full battery
of tests.

285
00:12:47,396 --> 00:12:48,646
Carbon dating?

286
00:12:48,714 --> 00:12:51,065
I'll pay cash
if it's not covered.

287
00:12:51,116 --> 00:12:52,567
That's nice of you
to float your friend.

288
00:12:52,618 --> 00:12:54,786
He's not my friend.
He's my father.

289
00:12:54,870 --> 00:12:57,672
He's 22 years
older than me.

290
00:12:57,740 --> 00:13:00,792
Well, that's true, he's
definitely had his jowls done.

291
00:13:00,876 --> 00:13:03,294
Statistically, if he didn't
have these symptoms,

292
00:13:03,379 --> 00:13:05,179
he'd be like most
people of his age--

293
00:13:05,247 --> 00:13:06,914
dead for the past
several decades.

294
00:13:06,966 --> 00:13:08,550
Do the tests.
I'm sick.

295
00:13:08,601 --> 00:13:10,935
You have a bad case
of natural causes.

296
00:13:11,003 --> 00:13:15,256
Do the damn tests.

297
00:13:15,307 --> 00:13:16,975
If the vial
fills with sand,

298
00:13:17,059 --> 00:13:20,261
we take that as a bad sign.

299
00:13:20,329 --> 00:13:21,329
Hugo should be here.

300
00:13:21,397 --> 00:13:22,513
Why'd you ask him to leave?

301
00:13:22,581 --> 00:13:24,599
We wanted to be able
to discuss this openly.

302
00:13:24,650 --> 00:13:26,601
But it obviously affects him.

303
00:13:26,669 --> 00:13:27,952
Honey,
let the doctor finish.

304
00:13:28,020 --> 00:13:29,437
<i>It's a standard procedure.</i>

305
00:13:29,488 --> 00:13:30,605
We use general anesthesia,

306
00:13:30,656 --> 00:13:32,090
harvest a very small
amount of--

307
00:13:32,157 --> 00:13:34,626
no. I'm not taking
my brother's marrow.

308
00:13:34,710 --> 00:13:35,776
Del, it's--

309
00:13:35,828 --> 00:13:36,961
<i>these harvests</i>
<i>are harmless.</i>

310
00:13:37,046 --> 00:13:38,079
With the meds we give,

311
00:13:38,147 --> 00:13:39,581
there's almost no pain,

312
00:13:39,648 --> 00:13:40,632
almost no risk of infection.

313
00:13:40,716 --> 00:13:42,800
Almost?

314
00:13:42,868 --> 00:13:47,205
His life's hard enough
as it is.

315
00:13:47,273 --> 00:13:49,173
<i>(Taub)</i>
<i>Small problem</i>
<i>with the treatment.</i>

316
00:13:49,241 --> 00:13:52,393
Patient won't take marrow
from steel wheels?

317
00:13:52,461 --> 00:13:53,928
We're finding
another match.

318
00:13:53,979 --> 00:13:55,096
And how do you know?

319
00:13:55,147 --> 00:13:56,964
What other problem
could there be

320
00:13:57,016 --> 00:13:58,633
with a problem-free
procedure?

321
00:13:58,701 --> 00:14:00,852
Boy's sports,
science club,

322
00:14:00,936 --> 00:14:03,137
she's living his life,
not hers.

323
00:14:03,188 --> 00:14:05,156
Makes sense she's being
a self-denying moron.

324
00:14:05,240 --> 00:14:06,240
She loves her brother.

325
00:14:06,308 --> 00:14:07,442
She's thinking
selflessly.

326
00:14:07,509 --> 00:14:08,476
How is that at all--

327
00:14:08,527 --> 00:14:09,494
being moronic?

328
00:14:09,578 --> 00:14:10,811
Mm.
If I can only think

329
00:14:10,863 --> 00:14:11,979
of a harm-free
medical treatment

330
00:14:12,031 --> 00:14:12,964
she turned down lately.

331
00:14:13,032 --> 00:14:14,032
You're right.

332
00:14:14,116 --> 00:14:15,199
If everyone
were more selfish,

333
00:14:15,284 --> 00:14:16,618
the world would be
a better place.

334
00:14:16,669 --> 00:14:19,120
See? I can skip
the idiot part

335
00:14:19,171 --> 00:14:22,340
when you're not
being an idiot.

336
00:14:22,424 --> 00:14:24,676
Yeah, I had that
same facial expression

337
00:14:24,760 --> 00:14:26,010
for the first 48 hours.

338
00:14:26,095 --> 00:14:27,295
Had another one too,

339
00:14:27,346 --> 00:14:29,681
but only for
15 seconds at a time.

340
00:14:29,765 --> 00:14:31,182
I'm happy for you.
You're happy for you.

341
00:14:31,266 --> 00:14:33,167
This is huge.

342
00:14:33,218 --> 00:14:35,269
So who's gonna
supervise you?

343
00:14:35,337 --> 00:14:36,888
Cuddy.

344
00:14:36,972 --> 00:14:39,557
Well, I guess
maybe that can work.

345
00:14:39,642 --> 00:14:42,026
Maybe?
Nothing's changed.

346
00:14:42,111 --> 00:14:45,229
You showed up for clinic hours.
Voluntarily.

347
00:14:45,314 --> 00:14:47,532
Fine.
A little bit has changed.

348
00:14:47,616 --> 00:14:48,650
House,
everything's changed.

349
00:14:48,701 --> 00:14:49,850
You're sleeping together.

350
00:14:49,902 --> 00:14:51,319
You want something from her

351
00:14:51,370 --> 00:14:54,188
besides a sign-off on scaring
your patient to death.

352
00:14:54,239 --> 00:14:55,473
You talked to Taub.

353
00:14:55,541 --> 00:14:57,091
He's worried about you.

354
00:14:57,159 --> 00:14:58,042
He's a jerk.

355
00:14:58,127 --> 00:14:59,427
I'm worried too.

356
00:14:59,495 --> 00:15:00,395
Do I need to say it?

357
00:15:00,462 --> 00:15:02,430
I want this to work.

358
00:15:02,498 --> 00:15:04,415
I'm not doing
anything differently.

359
00:15:04,500 --> 00:15:06,751
She changed my mind
about one diagnostic test.

360
00:15:06,835 --> 00:15:08,803
And she was right.

361
00:15:08,870 --> 00:15:10,838
Even though it's your
emotional default,

362
00:15:10,889 --> 00:15:13,040
<i>stop worrying.</i>

363
00:15:13,092 --> 00:15:16,995
I can handle it.

364
00:15:17,062 --> 00:15:19,313
I hear you're a pretty
fierce skateboarder.

365
00:15:19,381 --> 00:15:21,432
I do okay.

366
00:15:21,517 --> 00:15:22,567
All your activities,

367
00:15:22,651 --> 00:15:25,553
don't they seem like things

368
00:15:25,604 --> 00:15:27,572
a 16-year-old boy
would do?

369
00:15:27,656 --> 00:15:29,791
Some people might think

370
00:15:29,858 --> 00:15:32,026
you're trying to live
his life for him.

371
00:15:32,077 --> 00:15:35,496
I am. Sort of.

372
00:15:35,564 --> 00:15:36,581
Um,
I got into skateboarding

373
00:15:36,665 --> 00:15:37,965
when some of Hugo's
classmates did,

374
00:15:38,033 --> 00:15:41,085
and he realized
he could never do it.

375
00:15:41,170 --> 00:15:43,838
It's the same
with a lot of things.

376
00:15:43,905 --> 00:15:46,741
We live through it
together.

377
00:15:46,809 --> 00:15:49,210
And you're not worried
you're being selfless

378
00:15:49,261 --> 00:15:51,596
to the point
of self-denial?

379
00:15:51,680 --> 00:15:54,665
You've never been
inspired by someone?

380
00:15:54,733 --> 00:15:58,753
Why don't you
take your pills?

381
00:15:58,804 --> 00:16:00,688
[Coughs, gasps]

382
00:16:00,756 --> 00:16:04,442
Need some help in here.

383
00:16:04,526 --> 00:16:06,360
<i>Hemothorax.</i>
<i>We need to bronch her now.</i>

384
00:16:06,428 --> 00:16:07,528
Clear an O.R.

385
00:16:07,596 --> 00:16:09,363
She's drowning
in her own blood.

386
00:16:09,431 --> 00:16:11,449
<i>It's not amyloidosis.</i>

387
00:16:19,225 --> 00:16:20,809
<i>She's bleeding to death.</i>

388
00:16:20,877 --> 00:16:22,878
Out of her lung.

389
00:16:22,946 --> 00:16:25,314
I want to fill
a quarter of it with foam.

390
00:16:25,382 --> 00:16:27,716
That'd stop the bleeding,
all right.

391
00:16:27,784 --> 00:16:30,986
Thought it made more sense
than diet and exercise.

392
00:16:31,054 --> 00:16:32,905
And if she doesn't have
enough lung function left,

393
00:16:32,989 --> 00:16:34,173
you'll have killed her.

394
00:16:34,240 --> 00:16:36,659
The only alternative
is slowly suturing the lung,

395
00:16:36,726 --> 00:16:38,360
hoping that the bleeding
stops in time

396
00:16:38,411 --> 00:16:39,878
and she doesn't die
on her own.

397
00:16:39,946 --> 00:16:42,164
But we would walk away
with clean hands.

398
00:16:42,232 --> 00:16:44,083
Except for all the blood.

399
00:16:47,671 --> 00:16:49,121
You're right.

400
00:16:49,205 --> 00:16:50,422
Faster and riskier's better.

401
00:16:50,507 --> 00:16:52,007
Foam the lung.

402
00:16:58,498 --> 00:17:00,065
Got a green light?

403
00:17:04,320 --> 00:17:08,190
No.
Suture the lung.

404
00:17:08,257 --> 00:17:10,726
<i>Scalpel,</i>
<i>rib spreader.</i>

405
00:17:14,781 --> 00:17:17,099
I can't handle it.

406
00:17:19,819 --> 00:17:21,036
What happened?

407
00:17:21,104 --> 00:17:24,957
She said "yes,"
and I heard "no."

408
00:17:25,041 --> 00:17:26,291
I didn't actually
hear "no."

409
00:17:26,376 --> 00:17:29,828
But I just...Was sure
that's what she meant.

410
00:17:29,913 --> 00:17:34,366
Way she tilted her head
and half-arched her eyebrow.

411
00:17:34,434 --> 00:17:36,085
What do I even care
what she meant?

412
00:17:36,136 --> 00:17:40,122
She said yes.
That's all that matters.

413
00:17:40,173 --> 00:17:42,124
I'm screwing this up.

414
00:17:42,192 --> 00:17:44,810
It's not completely bad,
House.

415
00:17:44,894 --> 00:17:46,478
You care enough
to pull your punches.

416
00:17:46,563 --> 00:17:47,730
That's not a bad thing.

417
00:17:47,797 --> 00:17:50,065
But you and Cuddy
have got to figure out a way

418
00:17:50,133 --> 00:17:51,834
of avoiding this problem.

419
00:17:51,901 --> 00:17:55,020
Set some ground rules.

420
00:17:55,088 --> 00:17:57,372
Yeah.

421
00:17:57,440 --> 00:17:59,925
I have to avoid
this problem.

422
00:17:59,993 --> 00:18:02,144
If I can restrict
our interactions

423
00:18:02,195 --> 00:18:04,980
to places where neither of us
are wearing pants...

424
00:18:05,031 --> 00:18:07,116
Yeah, that's not
avoiding the problem,

425
00:18:07,183 --> 00:18:09,785
that's avoiding the issue.

426
00:18:09,836 --> 00:18:12,538
Since avoidance is my plan
for dealing with the issue,

427
00:18:12,622 --> 00:18:15,424
technically,
that's not avoiding it.

428
00:18:15,491 --> 00:18:17,192
Thanks.

429
00:18:17,260 --> 00:18:18,210
No problem.

430
00:18:18,278 --> 00:18:21,496
[Door closes]

431
00:18:21,548 --> 00:18:23,265
Stitching worked.

432
00:18:23,332 --> 00:18:24,266
This time.

433
00:18:24,333 --> 00:18:25,467
No guarantee bowing to Cuddy

434
00:18:25,518 --> 00:18:27,686
will work next time.

435
00:18:27,771 --> 00:18:29,938
Heart arrhythmia,
kidney failure,

436
00:18:30,006 --> 00:18:31,690
and now bleeding lung.

437
00:18:31,775 --> 00:18:33,859
I don't want to criticize
your girlfriend, but--

438
00:18:33,943 --> 00:18:35,027
hey, you've been on me
for years

439
00:18:35,111 --> 00:18:36,511
to respect someone's opinion.

440
00:18:36,563 --> 00:18:38,013
Just 'cause I had
to go outside this group

441
00:18:38,064 --> 00:18:39,014
to find one I respect.

442
00:18:39,065 --> 00:18:40,432
Multi-system involvement

443
00:18:40,500 --> 00:18:41,450
centered in the lung.

444
00:18:41,517 --> 00:18:42,568
Sarcoidosis?

445
00:18:42,652 --> 00:18:44,036
Doesn't explain
the hemothorax.

446
00:18:44,120 --> 00:18:45,454
<i>Tb can affect</i>
<i>all three organs.</i>

447
00:18:45,521 --> 00:18:46,738
Skin test was negative.

448
00:18:46,806 --> 00:18:48,040
<i>What about</i>
<i>goodpasture's?</i>

449
00:18:48,124 --> 00:18:51,110
Affects the lungs,
kidneys.

450
00:18:51,177 --> 00:18:54,379
And autoimmune explains
the out of the blue arrhythmia.

451
00:18:54,464 --> 00:18:55,681
Goodpasture's it is.

452
00:18:55,748 --> 00:18:58,533
Immunosuppressants and
plasmapheresis to treat,

453
00:18:58,585 --> 00:19:00,886
kidney biopsy to confirm.

454
00:19:05,758 --> 00:19:09,544
[Announcements over P.A.]

455
00:19:09,596 --> 00:19:12,014
<i>Dr. House.</i>

456
00:19:12,065 --> 00:19:14,983
Don't tell me, your father's
hairline is receding,

457
00:19:15,051 --> 00:19:16,384
and he needs more tests.

458
00:19:16,436 --> 00:19:17,853
He's 102.

459
00:19:17,904 --> 00:19:20,155
His next test is an autopsy.

460
00:19:20,223 --> 00:19:21,723
Look,
I love the old man,

461
00:19:21,791 --> 00:19:24,443
but I got to get him
out of the damn House.

462
00:19:24,527 --> 00:19:26,628
He can't do anything
without me.

463
00:19:26,696 --> 00:19:30,199
He needs to be
in a care facility.

464
00:19:30,250 --> 00:19:32,084
Well, so tell him.
He's a big boy now.

465
00:19:32,168 --> 00:19:34,837
I can't.
I'm his whole life.

466
00:19:34,904 --> 00:19:37,906
But if it comes
from a doctor...

467
00:19:44,347 --> 00:19:46,765
That's very generous.
When you were 30.

468
00:19:50,136 --> 00:19:52,254
Pretend to run the tests,

469
00:19:52,305 --> 00:19:55,057
and then tell him...

470
00:19:55,108 --> 00:19:57,392
He can't live with me
anymore.

471
00:20:07,904 --> 00:20:10,739
I didn't run into you
all afternoon.

472
00:20:10,790 --> 00:20:12,291
I missed you.

473
00:20:12,375 --> 00:20:15,777
Busy day.

474
00:20:15,828 --> 00:20:20,448
Maybe we should
plan on lunch tomorrow.

475
00:20:20,500 --> 00:20:26,838
Problem is, at lunch
you tend to wear tops.

476
00:20:26,923 --> 00:20:29,474
This is much better.

477
00:20:32,929 --> 00:20:35,597
[Phone rings]

478
00:20:41,137 --> 00:20:42,971
Cuddy and I are naked.

479
00:20:43,022 --> 00:20:44,973
So I'm having
trouble focusing.

480
00:20:45,024 --> 00:20:45,941
Use small words.

481
00:20:45,992 --> 00:20:47,542
Kidney bioy was clean,

482
00:20:47,610 --> 00:20:49,311
so we rechecked the piece
of her lung from the O.R.

483
00:20:49,379 --> 00:20:51,930
You lost me.

484
00:20:51,998 --> 00:20:53,031
Sorry, who is this
calling again?

485
00:20:53,116 --> 00:20:54,449
<i>It's not goodpasture's.</i>

486
00:20:54,517 --> 00:20:56,385
There's intimal thickening
of the blood vessels.

487
00:20:56,452 --> 00:20:58,036
<i>And lymphocytic infiltrate.</i>

488
00:20:58,121 --> 00:20:59,321
<i>We tested for lam.</i>
<i>It's positive.</i>

489
00:20:59,372 --> 00:21:00,606
Plus her lung's fried.

490
00:21:00,673 --> 00:21:02,074
She needs
a donor lung to live,

491
00:21:02,141 --> 00:21:03,926
<i>which is the only treatment</i>
<i>for lam, anyway.</i>

492
00:21:03,993 --> 00:21:05,594
Taub's gone to
the transplant committee.

493
00:21:05,661 --> 00:21:06,912
They may have found
a donor lung.

494
00:21:06,980 --> 00:21:10,382
So this call
is purely expositional.

495
00:21:10,466 --> 00:21:14,186
[Shuts cell phone]

496
00:21:14,270 --> 00:21:15,537
I should really
get dressed.

497
00:21:15,605 --> 00:21:17,105
I told the nanny
I'd be home by 9:00.

498
00:21:17,173 --> 00:21:19,691
And I slipped
the nanny 40 bucks,

499
00:21:19,759 --> 00:21:22,261
told her to stay
till 10:00.

500
00:21:22,328 --> 00:21:23,278
Really?

501
00:21:23,346 --> 00:21:25,314
Mm-hmm, really.

502
00:21:37,354 --> 00:21:39,989
Good news.

503
00:21:44,578 --> 00:21:46,579
(Foreman)
Surgery was uneventful,

504
00:21:46,647 --> 00:21:48,198
but the donor lung
started failing

505
00:21:48,265 --> 00:21:49,783
about an hour
into recovery.

506
00:21:49,850 --> 00:21:50,983
We know we're right
about lam.

507
00:21:51,035 --> 00:21:52,202
Tests confirmed it.

508
00:21:52,286 --> 00:21:53,653
That leaves us
with two options.

509
00:21:53,704 --> 00:21:55,255
Body's rejecting
the new lung

510
00:21:55,322 --> 00:21:57,173
or we should have
rejected the new lung

511
00:21:57,258 --> 00:21:58,741
because it's infected.

512
00:21:58,809 --> 00:22:00,043
Let's biopsy,
see which one it is.

513
00:22:00,127 --> 00:22:01,161
<i>No guarantee</i>

514
00:22:01,228 --> 00:22:02,512
we'd hit
the affected spot.

515
00:22:02,596 --> 00:22:03,963
If we give steroids
for rejection,

516
00:22:04,014 --> 00:22:05,331
it'd make
an infection worse.

517
00:22:05,382 --> 00:22:06,833
If we give antibiotics
for infection,

518
00:22:06,884 --> 00:22:08,351
it'd make rejection worse.

519
00:22:08,435 --> 00:22:09,752
Which worse is worse?

520
00:22:09,820 --> 00:22:11,254
If we treat for infection
and we're wrong,

521
00:22:11,322 --> 00:22:12,505
she'll be dead
within hours.

522
00:22:12,573 --> 00:22:13,857
And if we treat for
rejection and we're wrong?

523
00:22:13,941 --> 00:22:15,608
She'll probably hang on
a day or two.

524
00:22:15,676 --> 00:22:17,727
You're assuming
her rejection's hyperacute.

525
00:22:17,812 --> 00:22:19,863
Odds are, it isn't.

526
00:22:19,947 --> 00:22:22,899
Gotta head off
the worst worse first.

527
00:22:22,967 --> 00:22:24,784
I studied under
Dr. Seuss.

528
00:22:24,852 --> 00:22:28,037
Start with iv methylprednisolone
for hyperacute rejection.

529
00:22:28,105 --> 00:22:30,707
If that fails, we'll switch her
to broad-spectrum antibiotics

530
00:22:30,791 --> 00:22:33,743
and hope we're not
too late.

531
00:22:37,364 --> 00:22:38,748
Cat got your legs?

532
00:22:38,833 --> 00:22:40,400
<i>We just decided</i>
<i>to give meds</i>

533
00:22:40,467 --> 00:22:42,886
that could kill the patient
based on a guess.

534
00:22:42,970 --> 00:22:44,838
You need approval from Cuddy,

535
00:22:44,889 --> 00:22:46,556
and she'll want to take
the safer course,

536
00:22:46,640 --> 00:22:49,208
and you're gonna fold
like an origami crane, so...

537
00:22:49,260 --> 00:22:53,212
I'll just wait here
till we get our actual orders.

538
00:22:53,264 --> 00:22:54,714
Fine. You do it.

539
00:22:54,765 --> 00:22:57,200
<i>Tell her</i>
<i>she's being an idiot</i>

540
00:22:57,268 --> 00:22:59,536
for always choosing
the safer course.

541
00:22:59,603 --> 00:23:02,772
She's sitting on her ample,
if well-formed, bureaucratic ass

542
00:23:02,857 --> 00:23:04,190
while our patient's dying.

543
00:23:04,241 --> 00:23:06,326
We'll see who folds
like an origami shrimp.

544
00:23:06,393 --> 00:23:09,078
You want <i>me</i> to get
Cuddy's approval?

545
00:23:09,163 --> 00:23:10,413
I gotta be somewhere
important.

546
00:23:10,497 --> 00:23:11,814
Sitting at your desk?

547
00:23:11,882 --> 00:23:13,499
I'm running late.

548
00:23:30,434 --> 00:23:32,552
Forget the tests.

549
00:23:32,620 --> 00:23:36,272
I think junior might have
a few words to say about that.

550
00:23:36,357 --> 00:23:40,092
I love him,
but he can't let go.

551
00:23:40,144 --> 00:23:42,528
40 bucks says he can.

552
00:23:42,596 --> 00:23:45,198
I can't do anything
without him helping me

553
00:23:45,265 --> 00:23:47,200
like I'm senile.

554
00:23:47,267 --> 00:23:49,769
If I go back there,
I'm gonna rip his throat out.

555
00:23:49,837 --> 00:23:51,871
You sure you won't warm up
to him over time?

556
00:23:57,795 --> 00:23:58,912
Skip the blood work.

557
00:23:58,963 --> 00:24:01,798
Tell my son it's grim news.

558
00:24:01,882 --> 00:24:04,116
I need to be
in a nursing home.

559
00:24:04,168 --> 00:24:07,119
A private room.

560
00:24:07,171 --> 00:24:08,605
Make it a suite.

561
00:24:08,672 --> 00:24:10,390
Be our little secret.

562
00:24:12,292 --> 00:24:16,896
I sit around
on my bureaucratic ass?

563
00:24:16,964 --> 00:24:18,464
I was relaying
your words.

564
00:24:18,532 --> 00:24:20,833
I said well-formed.
I said well-formed!

565
00:24:20,901 --> 00:24:22,719
What were you--

566
00:24:22,786 --> 00:24:24,887
I needed to be aggressive.
You're an idiot.

567
00:24:24,955 --> 00:24:27,857
She was siding
with Foreman's analysis.

568
00:24:27,925 --> 00:24:30,159
The odds are against it
being hyperacute rejection.

569
00:24:30,244 --> 00:24:32,161
Stop.

570
00:24:32,246 --> 00:24:33,696
I agree with you.

571
00:24:33,764 --> 00:24:35,882
<i>That was our analysis</i>
<i>from the start.</i>

572
00:24:35,950 --> 00:24:38,117
If you've got a problem
with a team decision,

573
00:24:38,168 --> 00:24:40,119
you come to me.

574
00:24:40,170 --> 00:24:42,455
I'm sorry.
I-I'll deal with him later.

575
00:24:44,091 --> 00:24:46,526
I said well-formed.

576
00:24:53,517 --> 00:24:55,652
<i>People who have not</i>
<i>seen Cuddy naked</i>

577
00:24:55,719 --> 00:24:57,770
should not throw stones.

578
00:24:57,838 --> 00:25:00,640
<i>She does have</i>
<i>great cans.</i>

579
00:25:02,226 --> 00:25:04,176
Cuddy has House
on such a short leash,

580
00:25:04,228 --> 00:25:06,012
she might as well start
giving him chew toys.

581
00:25:06,063 --> 00:25:08,731
Let's give the antibiotics
at least another hour.

582
00:25:08,816 --> 00:25:11,401
Amazing. And House hasn't
given you one ounce of grief

583
00:25:11,485 --> 00:25:14,153
for your complete lack
of interest in his love life?

584
00:25:14,204 --> 00:25:16,489
Did it ever occur to you
that House is just happy

585
00:25:16,540 --> 00:25:18,357
and could give a crap
about other people's lives

586
00:25:18,409 --> 00:25:19,542
because of it?

587
00:25:19,626 --> 00:25:22,194
Well, that's ironic
and depressing.

588
00:25:22,246 --> 00:25:23,713
And by that logic,

589
00:25:23,797 --> 00:25:25,381
the reason
you don't give a crap

590
00:25:25,466 --> 00:25:27,000
is because you're happy,

591
00:25:27,051 --> 00:25:29,035
which means
you've got someone new

592
00:25:29,086 --> 00:25:30,970
giving you chew toys.

593
00:25:31,038 --> 00:25:32,371
You're 1/4th right.

594
00:25:32,423 --> 00:25:33,873
Wait.

595
00:25:33,924 --> 00:25:36,225
Are you saying...
[pagers beep]

596
00:25:36,310 --> 00:25:37,977
You're dating
four women?

597
00:25:44,217 --> 00:25:45,318
<i>(Chase)</i>
<i>BP's dropping.</i>

598
00:25:45,385 --> 00:25:46,903
Means the antibiotics
aren't working.

599
00:25:46,987 --> 00:25:49,522
Put her in trendelenburg.
Can you save the lung?

600
00:25:49,573 --> 00:25:51,858
Believe it or not,
we got a better chance now.

601
00:25:51,909 --> 00:25:53,776
This means rejection,
not infection.

602
00:25:53,861 --> 00:25:55,862
Start her on iv
methylprednisolone right away.

603
00:25:55,913 --> 00:25:58,114
[Machine beeping]

604
00:26:01,785 --> 00:26:02,869
Wow.

605
00:26:02,920 --> 00:26:04,904
You hate salad.

606
00:26:04,955 --> 00:26:07,590
She's really got you
tied up in knots.

607
00:26:07,658 --> 00:26:10,043
I caved.
Through an intermediary.

608
00:26:10,094 --> 00:26:12,295
I need a plan "C."

609
00:26:12,379 --> 00:26:15,264
What you need is a plan
that you actually develop

610
00:26:15,349 --> 00:26:17,717
with Cuddy.

611
00:26:20,137 --> 00:26:22,188
Antibiotics didn't work
and then steroids didn't work.

612
00:26:22,255 --> 00:26:23,439
<i>The new lung's ruined,</i>

613
00:26:23,524 --> 00:26:25,341
and it's not rejection
or infection.

614
00:26:25,409 --> 00:26:26,976
<i>The only two options</i>
<i>were wrong.</i>

615
00:26:27,061 --> 00:26:28,478
Unless it's not lam.

616
00:26:28,562 --> 00:26:31,064
It is lam.
The tests were positive.

617
00:26:31,115 --> 00:26:33,766
Then the tests
have to be wrong.

618
00:26:33,817 --> 00:26:35,768
Deep-fryer's working again.

619
00:26:35,819 --> 00:26:38,371
Still working on that?

620
00:26:38,438 --> 00:26:40,289
No, it was here
when I sat down.

621
00:26:40,374 --> 00:26:41,374
I need to think.

622
00:27:10,671 --> 00:27:13,072
I want to make sure
you're trying everything

623
00:27:13,140 --> 00:27:14,524
to save my sister.

624
00:27:14,608 --> 00:27:16,325
Everything?

625
00:27:16,393 --> 00:27:18,945
Well, that must be it.

626
00:27:19,012 --> 00:27:21,164
See, I thought you guys
checked the box marked,

627
00:27:21,248 --> 00:27:22,782
"try every other thing."

628
00:27:22,833 --> 00:27:25,251
I'm the one that's
supposed to die first.

629
00:27:25,318 --> 00:27:27,653
I'm the damaged one,
not her.

630
00:27:27,721 --> 00:27:29,455
She never even gets
a cold.

631
00:27:29,506 --> 00:27:31,591
Damage has a way of spreading
to everyone around you.

632
00:27:31,658 --> 00:27:33,759
For example,
your obvious emotional damage

633
00:27:33,827 --> 00:27:36,012
is now making me have
a philosophical conversation

634
00:27:36,096 --> 00:27:37,663
instead of dealing with
your sister.

635
00:27:37,714 --> 00:27:40,266
See how that might be
damaging?

636
00:27:48,976 --> 00:27:50,076
Never?

637
00:27:51,862 --> 00:27:54,063
<i>When was the last time</i>
<i>you had a cold?</i>

638
00:27:54,148 --> 00:27:56,732
Any minor aches,
swelling, anything?

639
00:27:58,485 --> 00:28:00,486
[Mutters]
<i>It's been years.</i>

640
00:28:00,554 --> 00:28:02,822
She never gets colds.

641
00:28:02,890 --> 00:28:04,824
I didn't ask when's
the last time she mentioned it.

642
00:28:04,875 --> 00:28:07,627
I asked when she had one--
even a tiny one.

643
00:28:07,694 --> 00:28:09,378
It's nothing.

644
00:28:09,446 --> 00:28:13,166
Sometimes my ears
ache a little.

645
00:28:13,217 --> 00:28:15,384
So now tell me
the rest of the nothing.

646
00:28:15,469 --> 00:28:18,254
M-my chest...

647
00:28:18,338 --> 00:28:20,339
Soreness.

648
00:28:20,407 --> 00:28:22,091
Some congestion.

649
00:28:22,159 --> 00:28:23,726
You never said anything
about that.

650
00:28:23,810 --> 00:28:25,528
I barely noticed it

651
00:28:25,596 --> 00:28:27,430
until that skateboarding
tournament in Denver.

652
00:28:27,498 --> 00:28:28,731
How long ago?

653
00:28:28,799 --> 00:28:30,633
A...Year?

654
00:28:32,636 --> 00:28:34,103
Cold's nothing
when I think of

655
00:28:34,188 --> 00:28:36,439
what Hugo
goes through every day.

656
00:28:36,523 --> 00:28:38,390
Yeah, we get it.
Your brother, the Saint.

657
00:28:38,442 --> 00:28:40,860
His sister, the martyr.

658
00:28:44,248 --> 00:28:46,449
Thank God you followed me.

659
00:28:46,533 --> 00:28:48,400
Now you can go back
to the transplant committee

660
00:28:48,452 --> 00:28:50,069
while I get confirmation.

661
00:28:50,120 --> 00:28:51,337
Confirmation of what?

662
00:28:51,404 --> 00:28:53,623
What causes low-level
cold symptoms for a year,

663
00:28:53,707 --> 00:28:55,791
can ruin two lungs,
is immune to drug therapies,

664
00:28:55,876 --> 00:28:58,427
and gets worse in cities
nicknamed mile-high?

665
00:28:58,512 --> 00:28:59,679
A clotting disorder?

666
00:28:59,746 --> 00:29:01,764
She has a nasty case
of sickle cell trait.

667
00:29:01,848 --> 00:29:03,916
Her heart arrhythmia
wasn't sudden at all.

668
00:29:03,967 --> 00:29:06,302
Screwed-up blood cells
screwed up the blood vessels

669
00:29:06,386 --> 00:29:09,188
which gave us a screwed-up
positive for lam.

670
00:29:09,256 --> 00:29:11,857
If she'd told us about
her symptoms sooner--like ever--

671
00:29:11,925 --> 00:29:13,359
she might not be dying.

672
00:29:13,426 --> 00:29:14,977
You were right after all.

673
00:29:15,062 --> 00:29:16,479
I never said sickle--

674
00:29:16,563 --> 00:29:18,147
if everyone
were more selfish,

675
00:29:18,232 --> 00:29:20,449
the world would be
a better place.

676
00:29:20,534 --> 00:29:23,369
So she's gonna die.

677
00:29:25,022 --> 00:29:26,289
Unless we can find--

678
00:29:26,356 --> 00:29:27,990
she burned through
one donor lung.

679
00:29:28,058 --> 00:29:31,961
Transplant committee's never
gonna give her a second one.

680
00:29:32,045 --> 00:29:34,380
Well, then I guess
you're right again.

681
00:29:38,335 --> 00:29:41,220
Unless we don't need
their approval.

682
00:29:50,184 --> 00:29:52,068
You can't advise
your patient's parents

683
00:29:52,153 --> 00:29:55,655
to take marrow and half a lung
from their son!

684
00:29:55,723 --> 00:29:59,192
I guess I can just chat
with them about the weather.

685
00:29:59,243 --> 00:30:01,578
Blood tests just confirmed
sickle cell trait.

686
00:30:01,662 --> 00:30:05,832
So they might be curious
about the <i>only</i> treatment option.

687
00:30:05,900 --> 00:30:08,101
Though we are having
weird weather lately.

688
00:30:08,169 --> 00:30:10,020
There is a huge reason
not to take lungs

689
00:30:10,087 --> 00:30:11,571
from living patients.

690
00:30:11,622 --> 00:30:13,240
So their siblings can die?

691
00:30:13,307 --> 00:30:14,908
Their son has cmd.

692
00:30:14,959 --> 00:30:17,894
As it is, he's gonna die
of respiratory failure by 25.

693
00:30:17,962 --> 00:30:19,913
We could cut whatever time
he has left in half.

694
00:30:19,964 --> 00:30:22,582
That qualifies as a bad reason
for them to reject the idea.

695
00:30:22,633 --> 00:30:24,518
It's a much worse reason
for them not to get the choice.

696
00:30:24,585 --> 00:30:26,703
It's coercive to tell them!

697
00:30:26,771 --> 00:30:28,305
You ever hear of
"do no harm"?

698
00:30:28,389 --> 00:30:30,106
That was second year, right?

699
00:30:30,191 --> 00:30:31,591
'Cause I had mono
all that fall.

700
00:30:31,642 --> 00:30:32,926
Their son's
not even our patient.

701
00:30:32,977 --> 00:30:34,277
Why don't we just
take half a lung

702
00:30:34,362 --> 00:30:35,946
from some guy in the clinic
with a toothache?

703
00:30:36,013 --> 00:30:37,263
That's a great idea.

704
00:30:37,315 --> 00:30:39,032
Now we can give
the parents two options.

705
00:30:39,099 --> 00:30:41,551
We don't compromise
one life for another.

706
00:30:45,072 --> 00:30:46,740
Okay.

707
00:30:50,211 --> 00:30:52,662
Okay?

708
00:30:52,747 --> 00:30:55,281
Seriously.

709
00:30:55,333 --> 00:30:56,616
You made an argument.

710
00:30:56,667 --> 00:30:57,951
If you don't want me
to defer to you,

711
00:30:58,019 --> 00:30:59,386
why make it at all?

712
00:30:59,453 --> 00:31:01,955
But are you
deferring to me

713
00:31:02,006 --> 00:31:05,008
just because
we're seeing each other?

714
00:31:08,262 --> 00:31:10,130
Maybe.

715
00:31:12,066 --> 00:31:13,900
Yeah. I think so.

716
00:31:13,968 --> 00:31:15,569
This is screwing me up.

717
00:31:15,636 --> 00:31:18,104
Why is it not
screwing you up?

718
00:31:19,740 --> 00:31:23,610
It is.

719
00:31:23,661 --> 00:31:26,312
I don't know why
I okayed you foaming that lung.

720
00:31:26,364 --> 00:31:28,782
I realized it was wrong
as soon as I said it.

721
00:31:28,833 --> 00:31:30,149
I knew it!

722
00:31:30,201 --> 00:31:31,868
I knew 'cause you
tilted your head.

723
00:31:31,953 --> 00:31:36,256
House...We are
screwing this up.

724
00:31:36,323 --> 00:31:38,541
I'm gonna call HR,

725
00:31:38,626 --> 00:31:42,345
find someone else to supervise
you as soon as I can.

726
00:31:58,178 --> 00:32:00,563
I've got your...

727
00:32:00,648 --> 00:32:02,449
Test results.

728
00:32:04,118 --> 00:32:06,319
<i>You have the metabolism,</i>
<i>blood counts,</i>

729
00:32:06,370 --> 00:32:08,939
liver and kidney function
of a 92-year-old.

730
00:32:09,006 --> 00:32:10,707
Which is great,
'cause you're 102.

731
00:32:10,791 --> 00:32:12,358
What's not so great

732
00:32:12,410 --> 00:32:14,294
is the average
life expectancy is 78.

733
00:32:14,361 --> 00:32:16,129
It is my recommendation
that you move into a home

734
00:32:16,196 --> 00:32:17,831
with round-the-clock care.

735
00:32:17,882 --> 00:32:19,499
Oh...

736
00:32:19,550 --> 00:32:22,085
I can't believe it!

737
00:32:22,153 --> 00:32:25,338
Can't my son give me
round-the-clock care?

738
00:32:25,406 --> 00:32:27,707
Not unless you've done
your two-year certification

739
00:32:27,758 --> 00:32:29,576
in tiburon swab technology.

740
00:32:29,644 --> 00:32:30,794
<i>There must be</i>
<i>some other way.</i>

741
00:32:30,861 --> 00:32:32,679
Just because he has
a little tingling

742
00:32:32,730 --> 00:32:35,732
and some trouble feeling
hot and cold

743
00:32:35,816 --> 00:32:39,436
and some difficulty--
you can't feel hot and cold?

744
00:32:39,503 --> 00:32:41,271
Not lately.
But at my age...

745
00:32:41,355 --> 00:32:43,156
Show me your teeth.

746
00:32:46,060 --> 00:32:48,528
Dentures.
Fairly worn.

747
00:32:48,579 --> 00:32:51,164
I'm guessing ten years old.

748
00:32:51,231 --> 00:32:53,733
Show me your denture cream.

749
00:32:53,801 --> 00:32:56,586
Why would he carry
denture cream?

750
00:32:56,671 --> 00:32:59,405
Because...

751
00:32:59,457 --> 00:33:01,091
He has...

752
00:33:01,175 --> 00:33:03,093
Zinc poisoning.

753
00:33:03,177 --> 00:33:04,761
But to get it
from denture cream,

754
00:33:04,845 --> 00:33:06,079
he'd have to take
so much of it--

755
00:33:06,130 --> 00:33:07,580
trust me, he never
leaves home without it.

756
00:33:07,631 --> 00:33:09,299
How much do you use, pop?

757
00:33:09,383 --> 00:33:12,435
About a tube a day.
I buy it online.

758
00:33:12,503 --> 00:33:14,587
So what does this mean?

759
00:33:14,638 --> 00:33:16,623
Bizarrely, it explains
all your symptoms.

760
00:33:16,691 --> 00:33:18,975
Better-fitting dentures,
you'll be fine.

761
00:33:19,043 --> 00:33:22,445
Medically, there's no reason
to go anywhere.

762
00:33:31,956 --> 00:33:32,956
Hospital rebate.

763
00:33:33,040 --> 00:33:35,892
You might wanna...

764
